The Normal Distribution

The Normal Distribution Functions in R

dnorm(x, mean = 0, sd = 1, log = FALSE)
pnorm(q, mean = 0, sd = 1, lower.tail = TRUE, log.p = FALSE)
qnorm(p, mean = 0, sd = 1, lower.tail = TRUE, log.p = FALSE)
rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 1)

Description

1 dnorm gives the density,

2 pnorm gives the distribution function,

3 qnorm gives the quantile function, and

4 rnorm generates random deviates.

Plot density and distribution functions using dnorm and pnorm

Understanding the central limit theorem by Simulation

The central limit theorem (CLT) states that if \(X_i\) are drawn independently from a population where and are known, then the standardized average is asymptotically normal with mean 0 and variance 1 (often called normal(0,1)).

That is, if n is large enough the average is approximately normal with mean \(\) and standard deviation \(/sqrt(n)\).

CLT with normal data

results = vector("double", 1000)
mu = 0; sigma = 1 

for(i in 1:1000) { 
  X <- rnorm(10,mu,sigma)
# generate random data
  results[i] = (mean(X) - mu)/(sigma/sqrt(10)) 
}
ggplot(data = data.frame(results), aes(x = results, y = ..density..)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Understanding Confidence Interval with Simulation

What does CI mean?

is_include <- vector("logical", 10000)

for (i in 1:10000) {
  half_alpha <- qnorm(0.025)
  conf_int <- mean(rnorm(100)) + (1/sqrt(100)) * c(half_alpha, -half_alpha)
  is_include[i] <- ifelse (conf_int[1] < 0 & conf_int[2] > 0, TRUE, FALSE)
}

sum(!is_include)
## [1] 493
# this sum value should be around 500 since we take the significance level of 5%

The one-sample t test is for testing whether the data has significant differnece with its mean value. That is to say, it is used to examine whether the data gathers around the mean value or it relatively scatters. To better illustrate this point, we use the following two samples:

The two plots above shows two datasets with the same mean value 0. However, all the data in \(x_1\) gathers around 0 in plot1 while \(x_2\) spreads much evenly in plot2. Therefore, the variance of \(x_1\) should be smaller than the variane of \(x_2\).

The t statistics is calculated as \[ t = \frac{x-\mu(x)}{se(x)}\], thus t1 should be bigger than t2. By one-sample t test, we say a dataset significantly different from the mean value at a specific significance level if the absolute value of t statistics is larger than the that of the critical value, or the t statistics locats outside the confidence interval.

# H1: mu < 8
# one-sided 95% confidence interval for mu
t.test(LungCap, mu = 8, alt = "less", conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  LungCap
## t = -1.3842, df = 724, p-value = 0.08336
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is less than 8
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##      -Inf 8.025974
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  7.863148
# The result below indicates that the variable LungCap is not significantly differenct #from 8 since the p-value of the t statistics is larger than 0.05
# two-sided, default
t.test(LungCap, mu = 8, alt = "two.sided", conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  LungCap
## t = -1.3842, df = 724, p-value = 0.1667
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 8

##  7.669052 8.057243

Constructing confidence interval and Calculating the p-value of t-test

# parameters
n <- nrow(data_lung)
conf_level = 0.95

#sample mean
x_bar <- mean(LungCap)
#standard error 
std_err <- sd(LungCap)/sqrt(n)

#get the quantile accoding to probability
alpha_lower <- qt(p = (1 - conf_level)/2, df = n - 1, lower.tail = TRUE)
alpha_upper <- qt(p = (1 - conf_level)/2, df = n - 1, lower.tail = FALSE)

#construct confidence intervals
(conf_int <- x_bar + std_err * c(alpha_lower, alpha_upper) )
## [1] 7.669052 8.057243
#t_value: (x_bar - mu)/std_err ~ t(df)
t_value <- (x_bar - 8 )/std_err
pt(q = t_value,  df = n - 1, lower.tail = TRUE) * 2
## [1] 0.1667108
# Comparing to the built-in function
t.test(LungCap, mu = 8, alt = "two.sided", conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  LungCap
## t = -1.3842, df = 724, p-value = 0.1667
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 8
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  7.669052 8.057243
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  7.863148

Two sample t-test

The two sample t-test is generally used to test whether the mean values of two datasets are significantly different from each other or, whether the difference in means for two populations is signifanct enough.

Write your own function for 2-sample t-test

function

two_sample_t_test_equal_variance <- function(x1,x2, Delta_0, alpha) {
  n1 <- length(x1)
  n2 <- length(x2)
  alpha <- 0.05
  
  #degree of freedom
  dof <- n1+n2-2
  
  S1_squared <- var(x1)
  S2_squared <- var(x2)
  
  #pooled estimator:
  Sp_squared <- ((n1-1)*S1_squared + (n2-1)*S2_squared)/(n1+n2-2) 
  
  x1_bar <- mean(x1)
  x2_bar <- mean(x2)
  Sp <- sqrt(Sp_squared)
  std_err <- Sp * sqrt(1/n1 + 1/n2)
  
  t_stat <- (x1_bar - x2_bar - Delta_0)/(Sp * sqrt(1/n1 + 1/n2))

  #one-sided p-value. 
  p_value <- pt(q = t_stat, df = dof, lower.tail = TRUE)
  
  #
  t_half_alpha_dof <- qt(alpha/2,dof)
  
  conf_int <- (x1_bar - x2_bar) + c(t_half_alpha_dof, -t_half_alpha_dof) * std_err
  
  #two-sided p-value
  two_sided_p_value <- p_value * 2
  
  #confidence interval
  conf_int
  
  rval <- list( p_value = two_sided_p_value, conf_int = conf_int)
}

Using and Test the Function

# arguments

x2 <-  LungCap[Smoke == "yes"];

Mann Whitney U aka(or) Wilcoxon Rank-Sum Test

It is a non-parametric method appropriate for examining the difference in medians for 2 independent populations. And it is also a way of examing the relationship between a numeric outcome variable(Y) and a categorical explanatory variable (X, with two levels) when groups are independent.

wilcox.test(x, y = NULL,
            alternative = c("two.sided", "less", "greater"),
            mu = 0, paired = FALSE, exact = NULL, correct = TRUE,
            conf.int = FALSE, conf.level = 0.95, ...)

Calculate Correlation and Covariance

Pearsons correlation is a parametric measure of the linear association between 2 numeric variables.

Spearmans correlation is a non-parametric measure of the monotonic association between 2 numeric variables.

Kendalls rank correlation is another non-parametric measure of the association, based on the concordance or discordance of x-y pair.

Functions: cor(), cov(), cor.test()
